GLM Assignment

Sarah Zirkle

September 16, 2021

Poisson Example

Bat diversity: The species diversity encountered per year relates to net nights.

In this exampple the response variable is a count and the covariate is a continuous predictor.

bats.glm <- glm(Diversity ~ Effort, data = bats, family = poisson(link = "log"))
summary(bats.glm)
##

## glm(formula = Diversity ~ Effort, family = poisson(link = "log"),

We can determine 95% CI for the coefficients, calculate exponentiated coefficients, and determine 95% CI for exponentiated coefficients.

confint(bats.glm) 
## Waiting for profiling to be done...
##                     2.5 %      97.5 %
## (Intercept)  1.7287962374 2.192645099
## Effort      -0.0008043622 0.001680065
exp(coef(bats.glm)) 
## (Intercept)      Effort 
##    7.134420    1.000518
exp(confint(bats.glm))
## Waiting for profiling to be done...
##                2.5 %   97.5 %
## (Intercept) 5.633868 8.958879
## Effort      0.999196 1.001681
ggplot(bats, aes(Effort, Diversity)) +
  geom_point(size=3) +
  stat_smooth(method = glm, method.args = list(family = poisson(link = "log"))) +
  labs(title="GLM, poisson distributed count data") +
  xlab ("Netting Effort") +
  ylab ("Diversity (Number of Species)")

batdiversity.glm <- glm(Diversity ~ Effort, data = bats, family = poisson(link = log))

Lets look at the diagnostic plots.

autoplot(batdiversity.glm)

anova(batdiversity.glm)
## Analysis of Deviance Table
## 
## Model: poisson, link: log
## 
## Response: Diversity
## 
## Terms added sequentially (first to last)
## 
## 
##        Df Deviance Resid. Df Resid. Dev
## NULL                      17     8.3334
## Effort  1  0.63847        16     7.6950

Because the model is fit with maximum likelihood, we get deviance table. Deviance explained by diversity is 0.6387 units, unaccounted deviance is 7.6950 and the total deviance (diversity + unaccounted) is 8.3334.

summary(batdiversity.glm)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = Diversity ~ Effort, family = poisson(link = log), 
##     data = bats)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -1.7573  -0.4260   0.1361   0.4646   0.8629  
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept) 1.9649309  0.1181771  16.627   <2e-16 ***
## Effort      0.0005177  0.0006308   0.821    0.412    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for poisson family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 8.3334  on 17  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 7.6950  on 16  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 81.093
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4

What does the report tell us?

  • coefficient tests: Wald z-value to tell us whether the estimate is significantly different from zero. Ratio of the estimate/SE (for species diversity 0.0005177/0.0006308 = 0.821).

  • The model looks fine for over dispersion (7.6950/16=0.48).

  • We transform the coefficient to make a prediction; remember that the GLM is predicting the natural logarithm of lifetime reproductive success.

If we want to know how many species 140 net nights is predicted to result in, we must account for what the link function did.

What is the expected yearly species diversity for 140 net nights? ANSWER=e^(1.9649309+0.0005177*140), or 7.670708 species.

exp(1.9649309+0.0005177*140)
## [1] 7.670708
ggplot(bats, aes(x = Effort, y = Diversity)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method="glm", method.args=list(family="poisson"(link="log"))) +
  xlab("Netting Effort") + ylab("Netting Diversity)") +
  ggtitle("Linear Model = Poisson Error Structure, Log Link")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Binomial example

habitat <- read.csv("BatHabitatQuery.csv")
View(habitat)
ggplot(habitat, aes(RTHeight, Use)) +
  geom_point(size=3) +
  geom_smooth(method="glm", method.args=list(family="binomial"(link="logit"))) +
  labs(title="GLM, binomial count (presence/absence)") +
  ylab ("Probability of Selection") +
  xlab ("Height of tree (m)")

model_habitat <- glm(Use ~ RTHeight, data=habitat, family=binomial)
model_habitat
## 
## Call:  glm(formula = Use ~ RTHeight, family = binomial, data = habitat)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)     RTHeight  
##    -3.58263      0.07012  
## 
## Degrees of Freedom: 71 Total (i.e. Null);  70 Residual
##   (88 observations deleted due to missingness)
## Null Deviance:       80.98 
## Residual Deviance: 73.15     AIC: 77.15
library(arm)
x <- predict(model_habitat)
y <- resid(model_habitat)
binnedplot(x, y)

coef(model_habitat)
## (Intercept)    RTHeight 
## -3.58263160  0.07011639
confint(model_habitat)
## Waiting for profiling to be done...
##                  2.5 %     97.5 %
## (Intercept) -6.0740440 -1.6676356
## RTHeight     0.0194992  0.1321125

Interpret the slope of the logistic regression. Dividing the slope coefficient by four will give us an approximate estimate for the maximum predicted effect on the response of a unit change in the predictor. Slope of tree height variable is 0.07011639.

In this case, a difference in 1 unit of height (m) corresponds to a increase in the probability of switching of 1.75% since 0.07011639/4 = 0.0175291. (*100 to convert to percent=1.75%).

summary(model_habitat)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = Use ~ RTHeight, family = binomial, data = habitat)
